"There is only one man my intellectual equal in Petershof, and he is not here any more," he
      said gravely. "Now I come to remember, he died. That is the worst of making friendships here;
      people die."

"I love them," he said simply. "I know them well, and they know me. You see I have been in
      this district so long now, and have walked about so much, that the very wood cutters know me;
      and the drivers give me lifts on their piles of timber."

"When we come to think about it seriously, it is rather absurd for us to expect to have
      uninterrupted stretches of happiness. Happiness falls to our share in separate detached bits;
      and those of us who are wise, content ourselves with these broken fragments."
